						<summary>

						<p>On a boulder in front of the natural cave called Āṇḍār-maḍam on the hill.</p>						

						<p><hi rend="bold">Rājakēsarivarman: Year 14: 894 A.D.</hi></p>						

						<p>This record may be assigned to c. 9th Century on grounds of palaeography.</p>						

						<p>It records an undertaking given by the lay disciples of a Jaina monastery at Viḍāl <hi rend="italic">alias</hi> Nandimaṅgalam, in the <hi rend="italic">eastern side</hi> of Śiṅgapuranāḍu, to protect and feed Kanakavīrakkurattiyār, the female disciple and follower of Guṇakīrti-Bhaṭāra of Viḍāl, her pupils and the four hundred female ascetics. The king of this record may be identified with Āditya I.</p>						

						<p>(Published in <hi rend="italic">S.I.I.,</hi> Vol. III, No. 92, Ibid., Vol. XIII, No. 245)</p>						

						</summary>
